    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-04-15T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-04-15T18:00:00-05:00" n="939"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d939">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">837.6363/547: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Cuba</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Braden</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Habana</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-04-15T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >April 15, 1944—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 8:35 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>387. Minister of State<note n="68" xml:id="d939fn68">Jorge Mañach y
                        Roberto.</note> advised me that Mexican tanker has unloaded 161,000 gallons
                    gas oil in Habana for Cumex and urgently requests that it be considered <hi
                        rend="italic">ex quota</hi>. I stated I would be glad to cable Washington
                    which would have to make the decision but situation <pb facs="0976" n="962"
                        xml:id="pg_962"/> was such that in all frankness I was not at all sanguine
                    that his request could be granted.</p>
                <p>I can see no justification for increasing Cuba’s supply of petroleum products. If
                    Cuban Government were to follow up, its proposal for trade of gasoline for gas
                    oil reported in Embassy’s despatch number 5729 of January 18, 1944,<note n="70"
                        xml:id="d939fn70">Not printed; the proposal called for a reduction in
                        imports of 6 million gallons of gasoline (to be offset in part by additional
                        supplies of <hi rend="italic">carburante</hi> for local Cuban alcohol
                        production) and the import instead of 6 million gallons of gas oil
                        (837.6363/519).</note> it is believed that all Cuba’s essential requirements
                    could be met. I consequently recommend that this shipment not be considered <hi
                        rend="italic">ex quota</hi>. Please instruct.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Braden</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
